```

Now we can substitute `eq2` into `eq1`.

```tactics
  rw [eq1, eq2]
```

So now we have `fun t => deriv f (interpolator x y t) • (-x + y)`. We need to show this equals `interpolated_deriv x y f`.

Let's expand `interpolated_deriv x y f t`. By definition, this is `∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`. This is the dot product of `(-x + y)` and `deriv f (interpolator x y t)`. Because `deriv f (interpolator x y t)` is a vector whose `i`-th component is `nth_partial i f (interpolator x y t)`. So the dot product is `∑ i, (-x + y) i * (deriv f (interpolator x y t)) i`. This is exactly `∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f (interpolator x y t)`.

So we need to show that `deriv f (interpolator x y t) • (-x + y)` equals `∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f (interpolator x y t)`.

These are indeed the same by the definition of the dot product. In Lean, we can use `funext t` and then show the equality of the functions.

```tactics
