`interpolated x y f(t) = f((1 - t) • x + t • y)`

To compute the derivative, we apply the chain rule. The derivative of `f(g(t))` is `f'(g(t)) • g'(t)`.

We need to compute `g'(t)` where `g(t) = (1 - t) • x + t • y`.

The derivative of `g(t)` with respect to `t` is `y - x`.

So the derivative should be `f'((1 - t) • x + t • y) • (y - x)`.

Now, `interpolated_deriv x y f(t)` is defined as:

`∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`

This sum is precisely the inner product of `y - x` with the gradient of `f` at the point `(1 - t) • x + t • y`. So, this should be equal to the derivative computed above.

